      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You have a few options if your employer hasn&#x27;t given you your rights as a victim of domestic violence and talking to them hasn&#x27;t helped.\n[more]\nYou can complain to Employment NZ if you have problems with domestic violence leave or asking for short-term flexible working. If you think you&#x27;ve been treated badly or unfairly you must first raise a personal grievance with your employer within 90 days.\nThe Human Rights Commission can help with bad treatment in a wider range of employment situations, including some people not usually covered by Employment NZ (voluntary workers, self-employed workers, pre-employment situations, like applying for a job).\nYou can get free, confidential mediation from Employment NZ or the Human Rights Commission. If this doesn’t resolve a personal grievance or a complaint of bad treatment, you can bring your case to the Employment Relations Authority (ERA) or the Human Rights Review Tribunal (HRRT).\nIf you choose the ERA, you have to contact it within 6 months about short-term flexible working arrangements, or 12 months about domestic violence leave. If you choose the HRRT, you should contact it within 12 months of experiencing the problem you want to complain about.\n[Source: Employment Relations Act 2000, ss 69AAG-69AAK]\n[QR: Want to know more about...; Mediation: Mediation intro; Personal grievance: Personal grievance - raising]"
      }
