        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You may be able to get parental leave payments for 22 weeks if you’re an employee or self-employed and you’ve worked for the qualifying period. You can get the lower of $585.80 before tax per week, or your before-tax weekly pay. You apply to the IRD - they will make the payments, not your employer. You can get extra payments as well as the government ones if your contract includes them, for example your employer can top you up so you get your usual amount of pay. The rules for qualifying for payments are different from qualifying for parental leave from your job. \n[more]\nYou can get parental leave payments if you’re the primary carer of a child under 6, and you’ve worked for one or more bosses or been self-employed, for an average of 10+ hours a week for any 26 of the 52 weeks before the due date or before your spouse or partner takes over care of the child. This test covers you if you’ve recently resigned, changed jobs, are a casual or seasonal worker, or had several temporary or fixed-term jobs during the 52-week period. You can transfer all or part of your parental leave payments to your partner if they also qualify.\n[Source: Parental Leave and Employment Protection Act 1987, ss 2BA, 4, 71CA-71CB, 71D(1)(b), 71M-71P]\n[QR: learn more about timing and qualifying for parental payments; Timing: Parental payments - duration timing; Qualifying: Leave - parental - negotiated to qualify for payments]"
