        "text": "Congratulations on having an interview! Refusing to answer an interview question you think is illegal might seem hard, especially if you’re being interviewed for a job you really want. Here are some ideas that you can try:\nIf the question seems like a casual ice-breaker, you could answer generally. E.g., talk generally about ‘your studies’ without specifically saying that you’re still in high school. \n[more]\nRevealing sensitive information (like confidential client information or trade secrets) about your current workplace or employer is likely illegal. This line of questioning is also illegal. A simple answer such as; “sorry, I can’t talk about that” indicates to the interviewer they have asked something they shouldn’t have.\nIf you think you’ve been asked an illegal question, you could respond with another question, like: “I’m not sure how this relates to the job, could you please tell me a bit more about the role?”\n[Source: https://www.careers.govt.nz/articles/illegal-job-interview-questions/]\nIf you feel you’ve been asked an illegal question and would like to make a complaint, you can lodge a complaint with the New Zealand Human Rights Commission:\n[HRC https://www.hrc.co.nz/enquiries-and-complaints/how-make-complaint/]\n[QR: Want to see examples of illegal questions?; Clearly illegal: Illegal interview questions - examples; Indirect questions: Illegal interview questions - indirect question examples]"
