        "text": "Dismissal can happen in a number of ways. If you’re dismissed, you can within 60 days ask your boss to tell you why. They need to give you reasons in writing within 14 days. You don’t have this right to written reasons if dismissed during a valid trial period, but if you ask at the time of being told, your employer’s duty of good faith legally requires them to give you reasons, even as a trial employee.\n[Source: Employment Relations Act 2000, s 120]\n[QR: Find out about fair procedure, constructive/without notice dismissal, dismissal when you&#x27;re sick or injured, or during a trial period, or for misconduct; Fair procedure: Dismissal - fair procedure; When sick: Dismissal when sick/injured; Without notice: Dismissal - constructive or without notice; Trial period: Trial period - dismissal; Misconduct: Dismissal - misconduct]"
