        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A union representative or &quot;organiser&quot; may enter a workplace to represent members by participating in bargaining, carrying out recruitment, discussing matters with members and providing information about the union to employees. They can also come in to support compliance with employment law, collective agreements and dealing with matters concerning the health and safety of members, and deal with things about a proposed or current individual employment agreement or its terms and conditions.\n[more]\nAnother reason a union representative can enter a workplace is to help a non-union employee with matters relating to health and safety if that employee has asked them for help. This reflects the importance of union representatives in giving advice and support about health and safety in the workplace, both to members and non-members.\nA union rep can only talk to an employee for a reasonable length of time and their boss can’t deduct pay for the time they were talking. A discussion with a rep is not a union meeting.\nA union rep should access the workplace in a reasonable way during the usual hours of work. They have to tell the employer why they’re there and show ID, and comply with health and safety. If they can’t find the employer or representative, they have leave in writing their name, union, date and time of entry and why they entered.\nA union rep can be refused entry for limited grounds, for example it might affect the security or defence of New Zealand or the investigation or detection of crimes, or if an employer has a certificate of exemption on religious grounds. \n[https://www.employment.govt.nz/starting-employment/unions-and-bargaining/unions/]"
