        "text": "You can’t bring a personal grievance for dismissal during a valid trial period. This means it has to be in writing in your agreement, for a specified period for up to 90 days from when you start work, and your agreement has to say you can be dismissed during the trial period without being able to take a personal grievance.\nA trial period isn’t valid if you’ve been employed by your boss before, even for only an hour. If it isn’t valid, or if you’re told of the dismissal after the trial period ends, you can bring a personal grievance for unjustified dismissal like any permanent employee.\nA trial period is different from a ‘probation’ period. If you’re on probation you can still bring a personal grievance for unjustified dismissal if you’re dismissed during or at the end of the probation period.\nIf you’re working under a valid trial arrangement you can still bring a personal grievance on grounds other than unjustified dismissal, like unjustified disadvantage or discrimination.\n[Source: Employment Relations Act 2000, s 67A]"
