        "text": "Your boss can’t deduct money from your wages just because of miscalculations or other mistakes. They can only deduct after overpayment if the payment was for time when you were away from work without permission, suspended, on strike or locked out, and because the payment method meant it wasn’t reasonably possible to avoid it (like equipment failure).\n[more]\nYour employer has to give you proper notice if they are going to recover the overpayment and do it within 2 months of telling you. For a specific pay deduction they have to tell you within 5 working days of the overpayment how much it was, and that they’re going to recover it. For other overpayments, they have to recover the overpayment within 2 months after telling you:\n• if you don’t have a fixed workplace, within 10 days of your next normal pay day; or\n• if you have a fixed workplace but aren’t there in normal hours, no later than the first day after your next normal pay day that you go there in normal hours; or\n• if you have two or more fixed workplaces and didn’t go to either during normal working hours on your next normal pay day, then no later than the first day you go to one of the workplaces, or\n• no later than your next normal pay day in any other case.\n[Source: Wages Protection Act 1983, s 6, https://www.employment.govt.nz/hours-and-wages/pay/deductions/]\nIf your boss can’t get the money back legally by deducting your wages, they can recover it like other debts. But you may not need to pay it back if it was done by mistake, you got it in good faith (e.g. you didn’t realise you’d been overpaid or mistakenly believed you were entitled to overpayment) and you have spent the money or used it in some way that would make it unfair for you to have to pay it back. \n[Sources: Property Law Act 2007, s 74B; http://communitylaw.org.nz/community-law-manual/chapter-19-employment-conditions-and-protections/your-pay/payment-of-wages-when-and-how/]"
