        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "An employer&#x27;s basic implied obligations to you as an employee (which exists regardless of your employment agreement), are to: provide you a safe workplace; pay your wages as agreed; treat you reasonably and fairly; not illegally discriminate against your for reasons such as sexual orientation, political opinion, gender, ethnicity or race; and, not act in a way which breaches the employment trust and confidence relationship.\nYour basic implied obligations to an employer are to: be honest; show competence and due care in your job; not harmfully affect an employer&#x27;s interests i.e. leaking confidential information; obey the employer&#x27;s reasonable and lawful instructions; and, not harmfully affect an employer&#x27;s reputation. \n[Source:https://communitylaw.org.nz/community-law-manual/chapter-19-starting-and-leaving-a-job/overview-of-employment-agreements-and-arrangements/]"
