        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In mediation, a trained person helps employees and employers talk about what is wrong and how to resolve it. Both sides must agree to go to mediation. The mediator helps them talk but doesn’t decide what’s going to happen unless both sides ask them to.\n[more]\nMediation can be fast, flexible and cheaper than the court system. There’s no set process, but the aim is to reach an agreed settlement. The process can involve a meeting between two sides and their representatives or can happen over phone or email.\nIf you and your boss have a problem you would both like to be resolved quickly, you can ask for a fast-track mediation option. A short time-frame is set, and if the problem isn’t fixed by the end of it, the mediator can make a final and binding decision.\nMediation can be used to resolve many problems, but not minimum rights in things like pay, holidays/leave, rest/meal breaks, and breastfeeding facilities.\n[Source: Employment Relations Act 2000, ss 144, 145, 147, 159, 159AA]\n[QR: Want to know how to access mediation, or what the outcome can be?; Accessing: Mediation - accessing; Outcome: Mediation outcome]"
