        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Being owed wages by a company that&#x27;s gone out of business is tricky. If a company can’t afford to pay its debts, it may be insolvent and be put into liquidation. Any secured creditors can enforce their securities first. The official assignee then collects and sells all remaining company assets and distributes proceeds among the company’s creditors. Preferential creditors are paid in priority to unsecured creditors.\nBeing employed by the company in the four months before liquidation makes you a preferential creditor entitled to claim wages owing (up to $22,160) as well as certain other payments. \nIf your wage claim relates to payments due over 4 months ago, and the employer hadn’t yet been liquidated, you’d be an unsecured creditor and you could file a claim with the official assignee to receive a share of any funds left over after the secured and preferential creditors have been paid. It may also be possible to bring a claim against the directors of the company in a personal capacity. As you can see, this is a long process that may not pay off.\n[Sources: https://www.raineycollins.co.nz/your-resources/articles/unpaid-wages-employer-going-into-liquidation-what-are-my-rights.html;\nhttp://www.markdonovan.co.nz/employer-liquidation/"
