      "name": "Does an employer have to accommodate a disability?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The courts have put a requirement on employers to make adjustments – ‘reasonable accommodations’ – in their business to give disabled people genuinely equal access. The words ‘reasonable accommodation’ aren’t used in the Human Rights Act, but the idea is.\n[more]\nThe adjustments needed will always depend on the particular person, their impairment, and the context – for example, if it’s a work issue, the particular kind of work they do. Your boss may argue that the changes needed for you to do your job would have been unreasonable, based on either special services/facilities, or risk.\nThey could prove you’d need special equipment or assistance that it would be unreasonable to expect them to provide. They can’t use this exception if they could avoid the whole problem by getting another employee to do the particular tasks that are an issue, without unreasonable disruptions.\nOr the employer could show that your impairment means you’d present an unreasonable (not minor) risk to yourself or others, and that what they’d need to do to reduce this risk to normal levels would cause unreasonable disruption. Again, your boss can’t use this exception if another employee could do the tasks.\n[Source: Case: [2011] NZCA 20]"
      }
