        "text": "‘Garden leave’ is not mentioned in employment law but is sometimes used to describe a period when an employee retains their employment, receives full pay but does not report to work. Garden leave can be useful when both the employee and employer agree to its use in a particular situation. \nAn employee is entitled and obliged to attend work. Your employer can’t make you go on garden leave unless you both agree (the agreement includes having a garden leave provision in the employment agreement, entered into in good faith). If your employment agreement doesn’t mention garden leave, your employer shouldn’t put you on garden leave without your agreement. It shouldn’t be used to get around the requirements for suspension (ie the requirements of appropriate grounds for suspension and following the right process).\nEmployees must continue to follow all their terms and conditions of employment while they are on garden leave.\n[Source: https://www.employment.govt.nz/leave-and-holidays/other-types-of-leave/garden-leave/]"
