      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is there a minimum age for working some jobs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Employment must not prevent or interfere with attending school. Young people aged less than 16 years cannot work during school hours or after 10pm or before 6am on school nights. Young people can, however, work any hours at the weekends or during school holidays and, during week days, can work before or after school. Some industries have minimum age restrictions. [Source: https://www.employment.govt.nz/starting-employment/rights-and-responsibilities/young-employees/]\n[more]\nAn under 14-year-old cannot work as a babysitter, au pair or nanny without adult supervision because it’s an offence to leave any child under 14 unsupervised.\nSomeone under 15 years can&#x27;t work on a logging site where trees are being cut down or processed, on a construction site, anywhere goods or hazardous substances are being manufactured, in work requiring lifting heavy weight, where the work is likely to harm the employee, or with any machinery or assist work with any machinery.\nThese restrictions also apply to people &lt;15 visiting the workplace. They don&#x27;t apply if the employee works at all times in an office in that area, or in any part of that area used only for selling goods or services. They don&#x27;t apply to visitors who are under direct adult supervision, on a guided tour or are in areas open to the public.\nAn employer can’t hire anybody under 18 to work in sex work, anywhere with direct access to gaming machines, or any restricted area of a licensed premises while it’s open for liquor sales, unless they’re preparing or serving any meal, cleaning, repairing, maintaining, altering or restocking the area of any equipment, removing or replacing any equipment, stocktaking, or checking or removing cash. \nEmployees under 20 can’t work in parts of casinos where gambling takes place, or undertake any gambling-related duties."
      }
