        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "As an employee you can decide whether you want to join a union, which union you want to join out of those that cover your type of work, and to resign from a union. You can’t be pressured to join, stay in or not to join a union, or discriminated against because you are or aren’t a member. \nA contract can’t force you to be or not be part of a union, or give someone who is or isn’t part of a union preference for benefits, getting or keeping a job, and opportunities for training, promotion or transfer. An employer can’t discriminate because someone is involved with typical union activities like being on the committee, being a negotiator, participating in a lawful strike, submitting a personal grievance, or applying for or taking employment relations education leave.\n[Source: Employment Relations Act 2000, ss 7 -11; https://www.employment.govt.nz/starting-employment/unions-and-bargaining/unions/]"
